Comment: This was a standard game between two low-ranked players. I annotated this game simply to try and improve my own skills and understanding of the game. I opened with e4 - the only move I've had much experience with.
Black plays the Caro-Kann defence.
The Goldman variation of the Caro-Kann plays d5 instead. I can't find this variation in the GameKnot database.
The Goldman variation of the Caro-Kann plays d5 instead. I can't find this variation in the GameKnot database.
Again, a less-than-common move, with a strong structure on white squares but very weak on black squares, a blocked white bishop and with no pieces developed.
Again, a less-than-common move, with a strong structure on white squares but very weak on black squares, a blocked white bishop and with no pieces developed.
I tried to push paws forward to stop black gaining too much pawn strength.
A strange move for the knight, with no support and no visible motive. Black is falling further and further behind on development.
A strange move for the knight, with no support and no visible motive. Black is falling further and further behind on development.
A strange move for the knight, with no support and no visible motive. Black is falling further and further behind on development.

With hindsight, Bg5 might have also been good. Black would have three options: move the queen, play f6 in contrast to his previous pawn moves, or play Be7, the best option. Instead, I played the less-confrontational Bf4.
This move served two purposes for me: I was able to defend the bishop and move the knight away from black's oppressive pawns.
This move served two purposes for me: I was able to defend the bishop and move the knight away from black's oppressive pawns.
A waste of a move on black's part.
c3 is also viable, with a view to pushing forward on the queen-side.
Pushes forward and forks the black queen and bishop.
Pushes forward and forks the black queen and bishop.
A badly considered move that loses the bishop and leaves a white pawn in a strong position. Allowing exd6 would probably have been better, as the pawn would have been left hanging and vulnerable.
Pushes forward to try and break black's pawn structure and free the queen for action.
